<P>
SMOKING LINKED TO ASTHMA IN BABIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Women who smoke apparently are significantly more likely to have children who 
develop asthma, researchers reported. "Children whose mothers smoke half a pack 
of cigarettes or more a day are twice as likely to have asthma and are four 
times as likely to use asthma medications as are children whose mothers do not 
smoke," researchers concluded in a study published in the journal Pediatrics. 
The researchers analyzed data on 4,331 children from birth to 5 years of age. 
Dr. Michael Weitzman, an associate professor of pediatrics and public health at 
Boston University, said the data the study was based on only indicated whether 
the women had smoked during pregnancy and not after their children were born. 
</P>
</TEXT>
